{
  "texts": [
    "Cognitive calculi have exclusively proof-theoretic and argument-theoretic semantics; no model theory is used, no possible worlds are used.",
    "Within the present study, as explained below, dialects of the cognitive calculi DCEC (deductive) and IDCEC (inductive) will be utilized, and this is what makes success in our case studies in Section 7 possible.",
    "We said that IDCEC is an inductive cognitive calculus.",
    "The great pioneer of modern inductive logic in any form was Rudolph Carnap.",
    "Carnap would say, and the logicians and mathematicians today who continue his particular approach in the form of what is known as pure inductive logic (PIL) (Paris and Vencovská, 2015) would still say, that \"There is a blue cube on the table\" and \"There is an orange sphere on the table\" should each be assigned)."
  ]
}